==Trivia== 
*In the comics, Wade Wilson became a test subject of Weapon X program scientist {{WPS|Emrys Killebrew|Dr. Killbrew}} and his assistant [[Ajax|Francis Fanny]] to cure his cancer. He was injected with a serum developed from [[Wolverine]]'s DNA, causing him to develop a healing factor that saved his life but horribly mutated him and drove him insane, leading Wilson to adopt the moniker of Deadpool and turn into a comedic mercenary. Despite being associated with [[mutants]], he's not a mutant (''Homo Superior'') himself, but a mutate or enhanced [[human]].
*In {{WPS|20th Century Studios|20th Century Fox}}'s {{WPS|X-Men (film series)|''X-Men'' film series}}, Wade Wilson is a [[Canada|Canadian]] who fell in love with [[Vanessa Carlysle]] but soon learned he had terminal cancer. In order to save Carlysle the suffering, he left her and joined a experiment run by [[Ajax]]. This experiment tortured Wilson and unlocked his [[mutant]] gene, but was disfigured. Wilson then went on a rampage, killing Ajax and getting Carylsyle back. Wilson then used his powers to take down bad people until one day, [[Sergei Valishnikov]] tracked him down as killed Carylsyle. Wilson spiraled out of control, but soon found hope in helping a kid named {{WPS|Firefist}} from his pursuer, {{WPS|Cable (character)|Cable}}. Wilson sacrificed himself for Firefist, leading Cable to go back in time and save Deadpool himself. Deadpool then used [[Cable's Time-Travel Device]] to save Carlysle.
*Deadpool is the fifth character in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] to break the {{WPS|fourth wall}}, after [[Groot]], [[Pizza Poppa]], [[She-Hulk]] and [[Rocket Raccoon]].
**Unlike the first two, Deadpool is the second character to break the fourth wall on a regular basis, following She-Hulk.
*The muzzles on Deadpool's twin pistols read ''"Smile"'' and ''"Wait for the Flash."''
*In ''[[The Art of Deadpool & Wolverine]]'', Deadpool and [[Wolverine]] bicker as they write all over the book.

==Behind the Scenes==
*Deadpool in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] continues the live-action incarnation of the character from {{WPS|20th Century Studios|20th Century Fox}}'s {{WPS|X-Men (film series)|''X-Men'' film series}}, who was portrayed by [[Ryan Reynolds (actor)|Ryan Reynolds]]. 
**He was also portrayed by [[Scott Adkins]] as [[Weapon XI]] in ''{{WPS|X-Men Origins: Wolverine}}''.
*[[Taika Waititi]] initially wanted Deadpool to appear in ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]''. However, this was not allowed, as the film was made prior to {{WPS|The Walt Disney Company}}'s {{WPS|Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|acquisition}} of {{WPS|20th Century Fox}}.<ref>[https://screenrant.com/thor-ragnarok-deadpool-crossover-mcu/ Thor: Ragnarok Director Wishes He Could Use Deadpool]</ref>
*One of the concept artworks for ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'' featured Deadpool fighting [[Proxima Midnight]] at the [[Golden Daggers Club]] arena.<ref>[https://thedirect.com/article/shang-chi-deadpool-movie-cameo Shang-Chi Movie Art Reveals Deadpool's Scrapped Cameo]</ref>
*There were talks about possibly including Deadpool in ''[[Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness]]'' according to writer [[Michael Waldron]], but the filmmakers ultimately agreed that the film was not the ideal place to introduce Deadpool and thus scrapped his inclusion.<ref>[https://comicbook.com/marvel/news/doctor-strange-2-writer-michael-waldron-confirms-deadpool-cameo/ Doctor Strange 2 Writer Confirms They Talked About a Deadpool Cameo (Exclusive)]</ref>
*To keep the film's tone from not taking seriously the rest of the cast, director [[Shawn Levy]] opted to have Deadpool as the only character who can break the {{WPS|fourth wall}}, not wishing to undermine [[Wolverine]] as the deuteragonist or [[Cassandra Nova]] as the antagonist.<ref>[https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/story/deadpool-wolverine-ryan-reynolds-hugh-jackman-shawn-levy ''Deadpool & Wolverine'': Inside the Superhero Movie That Plays Rough]</ref>
*According to [[Ryan Reynolds (actor)|Ryan Reynolds]], Deadpool was at some point considered to actually die in ''[[Deadpool & Wolverine]]''.<ref>[https://www.cbr.com/ryan-reynolds-marvel-death-deadpool-and-wolverine Ryan Reynolds Confirms the Massive Marvel Death They Considered for Deadpool & Wolverine]</ref>
*According to [[Wendy Jacobson]], in ''[[Deadpool & Wolverine]]'' there was once an idea referred to as 'Deadpool's Deleted Scenes Extravaganza'. Where it would have been revealed that Deadpool was secretly in every previous [[Marvel Cinematic Universe|MCU]] film, only his scenes were cut from each of them. This idea was later dropped from the film entirely.{{Ref|TMoDW}}
*[[Alex Kyshkovych]] and [[Erol Ismail]] were stunt doubles for [[Ryan Reynolds (actor)|Ryan Reynolds]] in the role of Deadpool.
*[[John King (actor)|John King]] was a stand-in and double for [[Ryan Reynolds (actor)|Ryan Reynolds]] in the role of Deadpool.
*[[James Gunn]] considered having Deadpool appear in the [[w:c:dcuniverse:DC Universe|DC Universe]] series ''[[w:c:dcuniverse:Peacemaker (TV series)|Peacemaker]]'' and even spoke to Ryan Reynolds about it. He would have appeared in the episode "[[w:c:dcuniverse:DC Universe|Full Nelson]]" as one of the inhabitants of the interdimensional doors that ARGUS looks through. This was ultimately scrapped due to all the legal loopholes that would have involved the character being allowed to appear.<ref>[https://variety.com/2025/tv/news/peacemaker-finale-james-gunn-salvation-checkmate-deadpool-cameo-1236545270/ James Gunn Explains How the ‘Peacemaker’ Finale Changes the DCU Forever, Why Deadpool Almost Made a Cameo and Not Having Plans for Season 3]</ref>

